Huot et al. [78] studied the effect of milling atmosphere on hydrogenation characteristics and composition of milled Mg–Ni compounds. For material milled under hydrogen, the presence of Ni lowered the onset temperature of MgH2 decomposition from 440 to 225 °C. By milling under argon, Mg2Ni was formed, which slowed the decomposition kinetics of MgH2 and raised the onset temperature to 263 °C. Zeng et al. [79] established a thermodynamic description of the Mg–Ni–H system and made an attempt to apply it to analyze the hydriding process of Mg–Ni alloys. The following reaction sequence for Mg–Ni alloys with <33% Ni was suggested:5\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
