Rowsell et al. [136] reported hydrogen uptake measurements on five different MOF materials and found that IRMOF-11 showed largest hydrogen uptake (1.62 wt.%) at 77 K and 1.01 bar. Figure 25 shows results of a detailed investigation of hydrogen adsorption properties in seven different MOFs conducted by Wong-Foy et al. [149]. The H2 uptake for MOF-177 and IRMOF-20 was 7.5 and 6.7 wt.%, respectively: saturation was reached between 70 and 80 bar for both MOFs. These values more than satisfy current gravimetric on-board storage requirements. However, volumetric capacities (~30 g/L) are ~75% of the DOE target of 45 g/L. Furukawa et al. [150] calculated the absolute adsorbed amount of H2 in MOFs:Fig. 25
High pressure hydrogen isotherms at 77 K for MOFs representing surface excess adsorption (data from: [149])9\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {{N}}_{{{\text{abs}}}} = {{N}}_{{{\text{ex}}}} + \rho_{{{\text{bulk}}}} {{V}}_{{{\text{pore}}}}, $$\end{document}where Nabs is the absolute adsorbed amount, Nex is the surface excess amount, ρbulk is the bulk density of H2, and Vpore is the pore volume. Experimental measurements always report the surface excess amount. Hence, based on the experimental measurements the surface excess weight percentage of hydrogen uptake in MOF-177 at 70 bar and 77 K was taken to be 7.5 wt.%. The calculated absolute adsorbed value was 11 wt.%, which may be technologically relevant.
